Loic Gouzer, the former Christie=E2=80=99s rainmaker behind the $450 millio=
n sale of Leonardo da Vinci=E2=80=99s Salvator Mundi, reached for a sailing=
 metaphor when I asked him about the vicissitudes of the current art market=
, which he calls a =E2=80=9Ctechnical market.=E2=80=9D Gouzer recalled raci=
ng with his father in Geneva=E2=80=99s famed Bol d=E2=80=99Or, the annual s=
ailing regatta down to one end of Lac Leman=E2=80=94and back. The Bol d=E2=
=80=99Or is famous for its wide range of sailing conditions, where boats ri=
gged to exploit the faintest whisper of wind will, in the course of the rac=
e, have to quickly reconfigure themselves to withstand a howling squall, th=
en revert to light and variable conditions. =E2=80=9CGreat sailors don=E2=
=80=99t do well on the lake,=E2=80=9D Gouzer explained. =E2=80=9CAnyone can=
 do well when the wind is perfect.=E2=80=9D

Gouzer, of course, is as familiar as
anyone in the business with how art trends, like the weather on Lac Leman, =
can change with a moment=E2=80=99s notice. In 2016, he was christened =E2=
=80=9Cthe daredevil of the auction world=E2=80=9D in a glowing New Yorker p=
rofile ( https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/07/04/loic-gouzer-the-dare=
devil-at-christies?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F18%2F24%2=
9&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F16%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Dema=
il_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) chronicl=
ing his themed sales at the height of the art market in 2014 and 2015; the =
following year, he would sell the da Vinci for a still unfathomable sum. Bu=
t Gouzer, in his late 30s at the time, also needed a change. At the end of =
2018, he left Christie=E2=80=99s, where he was co-chairman of Post-War and =
Contemporary art.

He returned two years later with an app-based auction business called Fair =
Warning=E2=80=94Gouzer=E2=80=99s attempt to bring his Bol d=E2=80=99Or
mindset to the art market. Gouzer has signed up some 5,000 collectors, and,=
 since reviving the app earlier this year, has achieved record prices for f=
our of the seven lots he=E2=80=99s sold. This Thursday, Fair Warning will a=
uction a Francis Picabia =E2=80=9Ctransparency=E2=80=9D painting with a $1 =
million estimate, an amount Gouzer described as cheap compared to a Contemp=
orary artist like, say, George Condo.

