This is Gouzer=E2=80=99s second outing with Fair Warning, the disruptive au=
ction concept he came up with at the beginning of the pandemic. In June 202=
0, Gouzer began selling art out of his Montauk garage on a weekly or fortni=
ghtly basis via the app, until his health forced him to suspend auctions in=
 April 2021. The hiatus meant that Fair Warning missed out on the easy mone=
y-induced frenzy of 2021 and 2022. That was probably a good thing.

Fair Warning, Gouzer told me, is committed to a sustainable growth model. =
=E2=80=9CFirst, I want to assert this business model of a conviction-based =
auction house,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CRight now, it is early days, s=
o it=E2=80=99s only my convictions. But I want to hire people who come and =
say, =E2=80=98This is what I believe in.=E2=80=99 I want to create a cluste=
r of minds or eyes that have convictions. Then I want to expand a bit
horizontally.=E2=80=9D As an example, he mentioned the Paco Rabanne armor d=
ress from 1967 he recently sold for $112,000=E2=80=94the highest price ever=
 for a dress at auction.

Gouzer holds an auction whenever he finds a work he thinks will appeal to h=
is audience. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re hyper-focused. They=E2=80=99re alert.=
 They know if they see something on Fair Warning that there=E2=80=99s been =
some reflection about it,=E2=80=9D he explained. =E2=80=9CThe way I do the =
selection process is I go after works that I would buy for myself if I coul=
d afford them.=E2=80=9D Instead of choosing works based on who he sees as t=
he potential buyer, Gouzer looks for art for which he can make a convincing=
 personal pitch. In his mind, he=E2=80=99s living vicariously through Fair =
Warning, assembling his own =E2=80=9Cimaginary collection.=E2=80=9D

This =E2=80=9Cvicarious=E2=80=9D approach is meant to address what Gouzer s=
ees as the main problem with the art market right now. From his experience =
at Christie=E2=80=99s=E2=80=94and Sotheby=E2=80=99s before that=E2=80=94he =
believes
the auction houses should set the tempo for the market like an orchestra co=
nductor bringing out the nuance and pathos in the composer=E2=80=99s score.=
 Instead, what we get right now is a market dominated by collectors=E2=80=
=99 impulses. =E2=80=9CThe phrase we hear all of the time is, =E2=80=98This=
 is what the market wants,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CBut the mark=
et is like a kid who wants candy bars. It goes from one sugar rush to anoth=
er.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=9CPretty Much Chaos=E2=80=9D

Gouzer is famous in the art world for his audacity and boyish charm, but he=
=E2=80=99s not without his player haters. His success with Fair Warning is =
sometimes met with dismissive shrugs from some in the art trade, who murmur=
 about =E2=80=9Cunholy arrangements=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a veiled reference to =
Gouzer=E2=80=99s history of aggressive tactics in finding guarantors and pr=
ying works off collector=E2=80=99s walls for his themed sales at Christie=
=E2=80=99s. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve heard this my whole life,=E2=80=9D he tol=
d me when I brought it up. =E2=80=9CWhen I was at Christie=E2=80=99s it was=
 always, =E2=80=98It looks too good to be true.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D

Gouzer claims that he wouldn=E2=80=99t even know how to manipulate results.=
 And, more to the point, he works with lawyers who have set the company up =
under the same regulations as Sotheby=E2=80=99s and Christie=E2=80=99s. Nev=
ertheless, the art trade, especially dealers, like to talk about
=E2=80=9Csmoke and mirrors=E2=80=9D in the auction business. =E2=80=9CI=E2=
=80=99m a bit tired of the innuendo,=E2=80=9D Gouzer told me, pointing his =
finger back at the galleries that send out sales reports at art fairs using=
