          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">This is Gouzer=E2=
=80=99s second outing with Fair Warning, the disruptive auction concept he =
came up with at the beginning of the pandemic. In June 2020, Gouzer began s=
elling art out of his Montauk garage on a weekly or fortnightly basis via t=
he app, until his health forced him to suspend auctions in April 2021. The =
hiatus meant that Fair Warning missed out on the easy money-induced frenzy =
of 2021 and 2022. That was probably a good thing.  <br/><br/>Fair Warning, =
Gouzer told me, is committed to a sustainable growth model. =E2=80=9CFirst,=
 I want to assert this business model of a conviction-based auction house,=
=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CRight now, it is early days, so it=E2=80=99s=
 only my convictions. But I want to hire people who come and say, =E2=80=98=
This is what<i> I</i> believe in.=E2=80=99 I want to create a cluster of mi=
nds or eyes that have convictions. Then I want to expand a bit
horizontally.=E2=80=9D As an example, he mentioned the Paco Rabanne armor d=
ress from 1967 he recently sold for $112,000=E2=80=94the highest price ever=
 for a dress at auction. <br/><br/>Gouzer holds an auction whenever he find=
s a work he thinks will appeal to his audience. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re hy=
per-focused. They=E2=80=99re alert. They know if they see something on Fair=
 Warning that there=E2=80=99s been some reflection about it,=E2=80=9D he ex=
plained. =E2=80=9CThe way I do the selection process is I go after works th=
at I would buy for myself if I could afford them.=E2=80=9D Instead of choos=
ing works based on who he sees as the potential buyer, Gouzer looks for art=
 for which he can make a convincing personal pitch. In his mind, he=E2=80=
=99s living vicariously through Fair Warning, assembling his own =E2=80=9Ci=
maginary collection.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>This =E2=80=9Cvicarious=E2=80=9D ap=
proach is meant to address what Gouzer sees as the main problem with the ar=
t market right now. From his experience at Christie=E2=80=99s=E2=80=94and S=
otheby=E2=80=99s before that=E2=80=94he believes
the auction houses should set the tempo for the market like an orchestra co=
nductor bringing out the nuance and pathos in the composer=E2=80=99s score.=
 Instead, what we get right now is a market dominated by collectors=E2=80=
=99 impulses. =E2=80=9CThe phrase we hear all of the time is, =E2=80=98This=
 is what the market wants,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CBut the mark=
et is like a kid who wants candy bars. It goes from one sugar rush to anoth=
er.=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
         </tr>
