         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s5">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Gouzer is famous in=
 the art world for his audacity and boyish charm, but he=E2=80=99s not with=
out his player haters. His success with Fair Warning is sometimes met with =
dismissive shrugs from some in the art trade, who murmur about =E2=80=9Cunh=
oly arrangements=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a veiled reference to Gouzer=E2=80=99s hi=
story of aggressive tactics in finding guarantors and prying works off coll=
ector=E2=80=99s walls for his themed sales at Christie=E2=80=99s. =E2=80=9C=
I=E2=80=99ve heard this my whole life,=E2=80=9D he told me when I brought i=
t up. =E2=80=9CWhen I was at Christie=E2=80=99s it was always, =E2=80=98It =
looks too good to be true.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Gouzer claims that h=
e wouldn=E2=80=99t even know how to manipulate results. And, more to the po=
int, he works with lawyers who have set the company up under the same regul=
ations as Sotheby=E2=80=99s and Christie=E2=80=99s. Nevertheless, the art t=
rade, especially dealers, like to talk about
=E2=80=9Csmoke and mirrors=E2=80=9D in the auction business. =E2=80=9CI=E2=
=80=99m a bit tired of the innuendo,=E2=80=9D Gouzer told me, pointing his =
finger back at the galleries that send out sales reports at art fairs using=
 asking prices, not the actual selling price. =E2=80=9CSometimes I am blown=
 away,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cby the prices I see on those art world PD=
Fs.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>The problem with many of the conspiracy theories that=
 crop up after a wildly successful auction is that they=E2=80=99re based on=
 an assumption of order in the art world. =E2=80=9CThe truth,=E2=80=9D Gouz=
er said, =E2=80=9Cis pretty much chaos.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s also a lot mo=
re complicated and contingent. For example, the unprecedented success of th=
e <i>Salvator Mundi</i> sale obscures how the painting originally came to m=
arket. The focus of that auction season was supposed to be an enormous <b>A=
ndy Warhol </b>painting made with stencils of Leonardo=E2=80=99s <i>Last Su=
pper</i>. That work was secured by Gouzer=E2=80=99s colleague <b>Alex Rotte=
r</b>. Thinking about Warhol=E2=80=99s interest
in Leonardo, and knowing that <b>Sandy Heller</b> was advising the owner of=
 <i>Salvator Mundi</i>, Gouzer was able to secure a $100 million third-part=
y guarantee for the work. Christie=E2=80=99s then promoted the two painting=
s as a crowd-gathering, museum-in-a-box package deal. The subsequent tour o=
f various cities proved the point. People lined up to see the =E2=80=9CLast=
 Leonardo.=E2=80=9D Christie=E2=80=99s produced a clever short film of the =
awe-struck crowds. <br/><br/>Because two bidders got carried away and pushe=
d the Leonardo to $450 million, we=E2=80=99ve forgotten that the Warhol als=
o sold for $60 million that same evening. It remains the eighth-highest auc=
tion price for a Warhol painting at auction. <br/></td>
         </tr>
